      <h1>How to Calculate Your Running Pace (and Hit Your Race Goals)</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Whether you are training for your first 5K or chasing a marathon personal record, understanding pace is the single most important skill you can develop as a runner. Pace tells you exactly how fast you are moving, helps you plan race strategy, and guides every training session. This guide breaks down the pace formula, gives you target paces for every popular distance, and explains how training zones turn casual joggers into faster, smarter runners.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <section>
      <h2>The Pace Formula Explained</h2>
      <p>Running pace is the amount of time it takes you to cover a specific distance, usually expressed as minutes per mile or minutes per kilometer. The formula is straightforward:</p>
      <p><strong>Pace = Total Time &divide; Distance</strong></p>
      <p>If you ran 3.1 miles in 27 minutes and 54 seconds, your pace is 27:54 divided by 3.1, which equals 9 minutes per mile. That is all there is to the core math. The tricky part is working with minutes and seconds rather than decimal numbers, which is exactly why tools like our <a href="/calculators/health/pace-calculator/">Pace Calculator</a> exist &mdash; they handle the time conversions automatically.</p>
      <p>To do the math by hand, first convert your total time to seconds. In the example above, 27 minutes and 54 seconds equals 1,674 seconds. Divide 1,674 by 3.1 miles to get 540 seconds per mile. Convert back to minutes by dividing by 60: 540 / 60 = 9 minutes exactly. When the result is not a clean number, take the decimal portion and multiply by 60 to get seconds. For instance, 8.75 minutes per mile means 8 minutes and 45 seconds (0.75 &times; 60 = 45).</p>

      <h3>Minutes Per Mile vs. Minutes Per Kilometer</h3>
      <p>Most runners in the United States track pace in minutes per mile, while runners in virtually every other country use minutes per kilometer. You will encounter both units at international races, on GPS watches, and in training plans written by coaches from different countries.</p>
      <p>The conversion factor between the two is 1.60934, since one mile equals approximately 1.609 kilometers. To convert min/mile to min/km, divide by 1.60934. To go the other direction, multiply by 1.60934.</p>

